# Roguebusters Architecture

This is a Rust roguelike using **bracket-lib** (rendering/input) and **specs** (ECS).

## ECS Is the Foundation

- **Components** = pure data structs (`#[derive(Component)]` in `src/components/`)
- **Systems** = pure behavior unit structs implementing `specs::System` in `src/systems/`
- **Entities** = IDs created via `world.create_entity().with(...).build()`
- **Resources** = shared world state inserted via `world.insert(...)` (e.g. `City`, `GameState`)
- System execution order is fixed in `DispatcherBuilder` in `game.rs`

## Modularity & Encapsulation

- One concern per module. Keep modules small and focused.
- Never reach across module boundaries except through well-defined types (components, resources, traits).
- Prefer **composition over inheritance** ‚Äî build behavior by combining components, not by nesting logic.
- Shared behavior = a `trait` (e.g. `UIElement`). Avoid duplicating logic across modules.

## Module Structure

```
src/
  components/   ‚Üê ECS data (one file per component)
  systems/      ‚Üê ECS behavior (one file per system)
  city/         ‚Üê Map and city generation
  deser/        ‚Üê XML/data loading (prefabs, items, templates)
  ui/           ‚Üê Rendering (elements/, modals/)
  input/        ‚Üê Keyboard/input handling
  service/      ‚Üê Layout/screen helpers
  util/         ‚Üê Shared utilities (rng, etc.)
```

- All modules are declared from `main.rs`. Add new modules there.
- Mirror directory structure with `mod` declarations.

## Parallelism

`specs` can run systems in parallel automatically ‚Äî systems with non-overlapping `SystemData` are scheduled concurrently by the dispatcher. This project is currently **single-threaded** (no `rayon` dependency, no `parallel` feature on `specs`). The architecture already supports parallelism; it can be enabled later by adding rayon and using `par_join`.

To keep the door open:
- Declare only the storages a system truly needs in `SystemData`
- Systems that share a `WriteStorage` for the same component cannot run in parallel
- Prefer `ReadStorage` over `WriteStorage` wherever possible

## Game Loop

`Game::tick` (bracket-lib) ‚Üí read input ‚Üí optional sim tick (specs dispatcher) ‚Üí UI render

Never put simulation logic in the UI layer. Never put rendering in systems.

## Building & Interior Model

Understanding this hierarchy is critical before touching `src/city/`.

```
City
 ‚îî‚îÄ buildings: HashMap<i32, Building>   ‚Üê keyed by building_id
     ‚îî‚îÄ floors: Vec<Space>              ‚Üê one Space per floor
         ‚îî‚îÄ partitions: Vec<Space>      ‚Üê recursive subdivision tree
             ‚îî‚îÄ (leaf Space)            ‚Üê actual rooms / businesses
```

**`Building`** is a physical shell. It has an `id`, `interior_type` (kept for
reference), and a list of floors. It does **not** own a business name ‚Äî it is
just real estate.

**`Space`** is both an internal node (when `partitions` is non-empty) and a leaf
(when `partitions` is empty). Leaf spaces are the actual rooms that get:
- `interior_type: String` ‚Äî the business category (e.g. `"speakeasy"`, `"apartment"`)
- `name: String` ‚Äî the generated business name (e.g. "Harrison's Tailor Shop")
- `entrance_wall: Option<usize>` ‚Äî which wall the door is on (set by `add_doors`)

Think of a `Building` as the physical structure, and each leaf `Space` as a
separate tenant/business leasing a room inside it.

**Generators** (`data/generators/*.generator.xml`) describe what prefab furniture
goes into a room. They are keyed `type="room"` and looked up by `interior_type`
at fill time. Each leaf space picks its own generator ‚Äî **do not** pre-select one
generator per building and apply it to all rooms.

**Key methods:**
- `Space::assign_leaf_businesses_with(f)` ‚Äî recursively assigns `(name, interior_type)`
  to every leaf via a closure; called during city gen
- `Space::fill(generators, fallback, prefabs, data)` ‚Äî recursively walks to leaves,
  looks up `generators.get_opt("room", &space.interior_type)` per leaf, then calls
  `fill_space` to place prefabs
- `Space::find_space_info_at(x, y)` ‚Äî walks the tree to find the leaf whose rect
  boundary contains `(x, y)`; used to identify which room a door belongs to
- `City::space_info_at_door(building_id, x, y)` ‚Äî convenience wrapper used by
  `PlayerAction` to display the room name/type on door entry
